{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Use British English|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Susan Hockey | image = | caption = | birth_date = 1946 | birth_place = [[Halifax, West Yorkshire]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = English | occupation = Emeritus Professor of Library and Information Studies | years_active = | known_for = [[Association for Literary and Linguistic Computing|ALLC]], [[Association for Computers and the Humanities|ACH]], [[Text Encoding Initiative|TEI]] | notable_works = }}
'''Susan Hockey''' is an Emeritus Professor of Library and Information Studies at [[University College London]]. She has written about the history of [[digital humanities]], the development of text analysis applications, electronic textual mark-up, teaching computing in the humanities, and the role of libraries in managing digital resources.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boot|first1=Peter|title=Mesotext. Digitised emblems, modelled annotations and humanities scholarship.|date=2009|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|location=Amsterdam|isbn=9085550521|pages=223}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About The Susan Hockey Lecture in Digital Humanities|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/dh/events/SusanHockeyLecture|publisher=University College of London}}</ref> In 2014, the University College of London created a Digital Humanities lecture series in her honour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Launch of the annual Susan Hockey Lecture in Digital Humanities|url=http://www.greatparchmentbook.org/2015/05/01/launch-of-the-annual-susan-hockey-lecture-in-digital-humanities/|website=The Great Parchment Book|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>
==Early life== Hockey was born Susan Petty in 1946 in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire]], and educated at [[Princess Mary High School]], Halifax and [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]. == Career == In 1969 she joined the [[Atlas Computer Laboratory]] at [[Chilton, Oxfordshire|Chilton]] in Oxfordshire. She became a founding member of the [[Association for Literary and Linguistic Computing]] (ALLC) in 1973 and in 1975 she joined [[Oxford University Computing Services]]. At Atlas she developed software for the display of non-Western characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chilton-computing.org.uk/acl/associates/permanent/hockey.htm|title=Susan Hockey|website=Chilton Computing|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> At Oxford she was instrumental in developing the Oxford Concordance Program from [[COCOA (digital humanities)|COCOA]], an early piece of software used in humanities computing. These tools have become central to the practice of the digital humanities in the United States and UK.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Vanhoutte|first1=edited by Melissa Terras, Julianne Nyhan, Edward|title=Defining digital humanities : a reader|date=2013|publisher=Ashgate|location=Farnham|isbn=1409469638|pages=131}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Siemens|first1=Ray|last2=Schreibman|first2=Susan|title=A Companion to Digital Literary Studies|date=2013|publisher=Wiley|location=New York|isbn=1118508831}}</ref>
From 1991 to 1997 Hockey was director of the Center for Electronic Texts in the Humanities at [[Rutgers University|Rutgers]] and [[Princeton University|Princeton Universities]] in [[New Jersey]]. From 1997 to 1999 she was Professor and Director of the Canadian Institute for Research Computing in Arts at the [[University of Alberta]] in [[Edmonton]]. In 2000 she joined [[University College London]] as Professor of Library and Information Studies, and from 2001 was Director of the [[School of Library, Archive and Information Studies]] at UCL. She retired in 2004.<ref name=eadh>{{cite web|url=http://eadh.org/susan-hockey-curriculum-vitae-publications|publisher=European Association for Digital Humanities|title=Susan Hockey - Curriculum Vitae & Publications|accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref>
In 2004, Hockey was awarded the [[Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations]]'s Roberto Busa Prize in recognition of "outstanding lifetime achievements in the application of information and communications technologies to humanities research".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adho.org/awards/roberto-busa-prize|title=Roberto Busa Prize|website=Alliance of Digital Humanities Organisations (ADHO)|publisher=Alliance of Digital Humanities Organisations (ADHO)|accessdate=2 July 2015|ref=adhobusaprize}}</ref>
She is a founding member of several major digital humanities-related associations such as the [[Association for Literary and Linguistic Computing]] (ALLC), 1973, and the [[Association for Computers and the Humanities]] (ACH), 1978, and an editor of the Association for [[Literary and Linguistic Computing]] (ALLC) Bulletin, 1979–83, chair of the Association for Literary and Linguistic Computing (ALLC), 1984–97 and member of the steering committee of the [[Text Encoding Initiative]] (TEI), 1987–99.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tei-c.org/Vault/SClist.html|title=Text Encoding Initiative|website=TEI 2008 Steering Committee|accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref>
